to organize your data in a way that makes it accessible by these very large compute

00:17:11.119 --> 00:17:15.800
services means that we can answer questions very quickly and then hopefully eventually

00:17:15.800 --> 00:17:22.680
cure a major disease. So in summary, running workloads in the cloud offers scalability,

00:17:22.680 --> 00:17:26.599
flexibility, and automation. Data lakes offer a single source for your data, but it needs

00:17:26.599 --> 00:17:29.880
to be organized to be useful. It can't be that chair, right? We can't just throw some

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:34.359
socks on there and just promise ourselves we're going to fold it later. Connected compute

00:17:34.359 --> 00:17:39.520
services allow for you to retrieve that data, and those sources really feel, if we do it

00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:43.359
right, really feel like we're working on a local compute context, meaning there's a really

00:17:43.359 --> 00:17:48.319
low barrier to entry if you're used to using just your normal laptop. And with that, feel

00:17:48.319 --> 00:17:53.839
free to connect with me on LinkedIn, Medium, or GitHub at Colby Ford, or if you're interested

00:17:53.839 --> 00:17:58.640
in what I do, you can shoot me an email at Colby at tuple.xyz. I'll take some questions.

00:17:58.640 --> 00:18:14.319
Thank you again, Colby. Appreciate it. So whenever you engage with a new team, what

00:18:14.319 --> 00:18:18.640
is like the first thing you try to address when it comes to these kinds of data lakes?

00:18:18.640 --> 00:18:22.599
I think the first thing is looking at all of the different types of analyses that that

00:18:22.599 --> 00:18:26.479
team works on, because then we can start to organize that data lake at the very fine

00:18:26.479 --> 00:18:31.800
grain level. Like if you're running a clinical trial, do you do IHC data? Do you do RNA-seq?

00:18:31.800 --> 00:18:36.599
Do you do whatever? Like all these different lab tests, whatever it is. And if we can identify

00:18:36.599 --> 00:18:40.520
those things, then it helps us to kind of plan for the future, so to speak, in a data

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:44.640
lake environment. And then it also helps us to understand, do you have really small analyses

00:18:44.640 --> 00:18:47.800
that maybe we don't need to make some sort of complicated compute architecture? Or do

00:18:47.800 --> 00:18:51.959
you have very large workloads that we need to plan for?

00:18:51.959 --> 00:18:58.400
Thank you. We've got a couple of minutes if anyone wants to send over a question. I am

00:18:58.400 --> 00:19:06.119
curious though, do you usually get some pushback from certain teams? Like not necessarily a

00:19:06.119 --> 00:19:11.000
team you're working with, but like an ancillary team, and typically which teams are those?

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:14.719
There's a couple. One of the biggest things is, since we're in a highly regulated environment,

00:19:14.719 --> 00:19:20.239
putting clinical data in the cloud is still for some reason very, makes people a bit nervous,

00:19:20.239 --> 00:19:25.119
which is really interesting because I've achieved GXP compliance plenty of times, done things

00:19:25.119 --> 00:19:30.479
that are on classified data lakes. Like it can be done. And because of all of these overlaid

00:19:30.479 --> 00:19:36.560
blueprints and regulatory and compliance offerings that you can overlay onto your Azure environment,

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:42.040
it's really not that big of a deal. But for some reason, there's a gap there between understanding.

00:19:42.040 --> 00:19:46.439
That's one. And then two, talking about the last talk, people were saying there's this

00:19:46.439 --> 00:19:51.280
kind of barrier to entry for moving from a proprietary language to like an R or Python.

00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:53.920
Let's say you don't want to move from that proprietary language that costs millions of

00:19:53.920 --> 00:20:00.640
dollars a year for no damn reason. Then how do you actually run that workload in the cloud?

00:20:00.640 --> 00:20:06.079
Or how do you connect that service to a cloud-based data lake? And it can be done, but it's not

00:20:06.079 --> 00:20:09.439
exactly as smooth as what I've presented here.

00:20:09.839 --> 00:20:11.239
Well, thank you again, Kobi. Appreciate it.

